This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on improving the performance of state-of-the-art models across a range of data sets and problem settings. Additionally, the paper proposes a new method for mixed sample data augmentation (MSDA) that uses binary masks obtained from Fourier space, which is a common technique used in computer vision. 

The paper also discusses the information theoretic perspective of MSDA, which suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Furthermore, the paper analyzes the performance of MSDA on natural language processing (NLP) tasks, which could suggest that it belongs to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper's focus on improving the performance of models suggests that it could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
